message.content:
pink primrose:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded with slightly notched tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Soft pink with darker pink or magenta veins radiating from the center  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals arranged symmetrically in a flat, open star shape  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Yellow central eye surrounded by small, subtle stamens  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Broad, ovate leaves with slightly serrated edges; basal rosette arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single flowers on slender pedicels, emerging individually or in small clusters

hard-leaved pocket orchid:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated petals with slight curvature, often pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pale greenish-yellow to creamy white, sometimes faint brownish markings or spots  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Three outer sepals and three inner petals, with one highly modified labellum (lip) forming a pouch  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent pouch-shaped labellum enclosing reproductive structures, visible column with fused stamens and pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Thick, leathery, lanceolate leaves, arranged alternately along the stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Loose spike or raceme with multiple flowers spaced apart along the stem

canterbury bells:  
-Petal Shape: Bell-shaped, flared at the opening, smooth edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Usually blue, purple, pink, or white; solid color without patterns  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five fused petals forming a single bell-like corolla  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central pistil surrounded by five prominent stamens with cream to yellow anthers  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Broad, ovate to lanceolate leaves with smooth or slightly toothed edges; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Pendulous, single flowers or small clusters hanging from leaf axils or stem tips

sweet pea:
-Petal Shape: Butterfly-like, irregular, with a broad upper "standard" petal, two lateral "wings," and two fused lower petals forming a keel
-Petal Color and Pattern: Varied pastel shades including pink, purple, white, red; often bi-colored or with veined patterns
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals arranged bilaterally symmetric (zygomorphic)
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central column of fused stamens surrounding a single pistil, enclosed within the keel petals
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Pinnate compound leaves with 2-4 pairs of narrow, lanceolate leaflets, plus tendrils at leaf tips
-Inflorescence Structure: Loose clusters or racemes of several flowers on slender, climbing stems

english marigold:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded, slightly ruffled edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright orange to yellow, sometimes bicolor with orange centers  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Multiple layers of densely packed ray florets in concentric whorls  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Hidden central disc, small tubular disc florets, same color as petals  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Pinnate, deeply lobed leaves with serrated margins; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary, large capitulum flower heads atop erect stems

tiger lily:  
-Petal Shape: Reflexed, curved backwards, slightly pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright orange with prominent dark brown to black spots evenly distributed  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Six petals arranged in a radial symmetry  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Long stamens with prominent dark brown anthers, central pistil protruding beyond stamens  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, lanceolate leaves arranged alternately along the stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Clustered upward-facing flowers on a tall, unbranched stem

moon orchid:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded, slightly oval; lateral petals often wider than dorsal  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Predominantly white or pale cream with a striking magenta or deep pink lip marked with intricate patterns  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Three sepals and three petals; two lateral sepals spread laterally, one dorsal sepal upright; one distinctive labellum (lip)  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent column structure containing fused stamens and pistil; lip often has a contrasting color with ridges or callus  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Thick, leathery, elongated oval to lance-shaped leaves; arranged in basal rosette  
-Inflorescence Structure: Upright spike with multiple flowers spaced apart, typically 3–10 blossoms per stem

bird of paradise:  
-Petal Shape: Boat-shaped upper petal; pointed sepals resembling bird beak and feathers  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright orange sepals with vivid blue and purple floral tongue  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: 5-6 prominent petals, with three large orange sepals and blue aromatic petals in a horizontal arrangement  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Stamens fused into a stalk-like structure emerging from the floral tongue  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, elongated, paddle-shaped leaves with smooth edges; alternate spiral arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Erect, crane-like inflorescence on long stalks with bracted flowers resembling a bird in flight

monkshood:  
-Petal Shape: Helmet-shaped upper sepal forming a hood, with smaller lateral petals beneath  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Deep blue to purple, sometimes white; uniformly colored without distinct patterns  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five sepals with one enlarged hood-like upper sepal; inconspicuous true petals hidden inside hood  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Cluster of multiple stamens and pistils partially enclosed within helmet  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Palmately lobed, deeply divided leaves; alternate arrangement along stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Raceme or spike of multiple hooded flowers along erect stem

globe thistle:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, tubular, spiky tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Metallic blue to purple, uniform coloration  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Dense cluster of small florets forming globe-shaped head  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Not distinctly separate; florets with prominent stamens protruding  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Spiny, lobed or divided leaves with rough texture; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Spherical, spiky flower heads atop tall, erect stems

snapdragon:  
-Petal Shape: Bilabiate (two-lipped), tubular with a distinctive closed mouth  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Wide color range (white, yellow, pink, red, orange, purple), often solid or bi-colored with veining  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five fused petals forming a single flower with two lips; upper lip has two lobes, lower lip has three lobes  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Four didynamous stamens enclosed within the corolla tube; single pistil centrally positioned  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Lanceolate to ovate leaves, simple margins, opposite arrangement on stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Dense, vertical racemes or spikes with multiple flowers clustered along the stem

colt's foot:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, strap-shaped rays, slightly uneven length  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright yellow, uniform color without patterns  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Numerous ray florets densely packed in a single head  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Lacks a distinct raised central disc; entire head composed of ray florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Leaves heart-shaped or kidney-shaped with scalloped edges; basal arrangement, appearing after flowering  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single flower heads on leafless, slender, scaly stems emerging early in spring

king protea:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, pointed bracts resembling petals; thick and leathery texture  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pink to deep rose with subtle white or pale gradients towards base  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Large number (20-30) arranged in a single, circular whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent dome-shaped, spiky central mass of small individual flowers (florets) densely packed  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Oval to elliptical, thick, leathery; entire margins; opposite or alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary, large flower head often exceeding 10 cm diameter; flower surrounded by colorful bracts resembling petals

spear thistle:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, tubular, spiky florets  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Vibrant purple to pinkish-purple  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Dense cluster of many tubular florets forming a globular head  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Not distinctly separate; stamens protrude slightly within tubular florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Deeply lobed, spiny-edged, lanceolate leaves; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Large, solitary, spiny flower heads atop tall, erect stems

yellow iris:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, slightly ruffled falls and upright standards; falls curve downward  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright yellow petals with darker veins or brownish markings on falls  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Three large downward-curving falls and three smaller upright standards arranged radially  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent central style arms yellow, petal-like, partially covering stamens  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Long, sword-shaped, parallel-veined leaves in a fan-like basal arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Multiple flowers per stem, arranged in a terminal cluster or raceme

globe-flower:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded, almost spherical petals with slight overlapping  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright yellow, uniform solid color without markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 5-7 petals arranged in a cup-like, globe-shaped cluster  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Numerous yellow stamens densely packed inside the flower cup  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Palmately lobed, kidney-shaped or heart-shaped leaves; basal and alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Compact terminal clusters of flowers held above foliage on slender stems

purple coneflower:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly drooping  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Solid purple to pinkish-purple, uniform coloration  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 10-20 petals, radial symmetry, arranged in a single whorl around the center  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent raised central cone; dark reddish-brown to orange-brown; spiky, dome-shaped disc florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Lanceolate to ovate leaves with rough texture; alternate leaf arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flower head atop long, sturdy, leafless stems

peruvian lily:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly curved petals with pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Multicolored with prominent speckles or streaks, commonly pink, white, yellow, or orange base with contrasting darker spots  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Six tepals arranged in two whorls of three, slightly overlapping  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Six stamens with prominent anthers, central pistil often visible  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Linear to lanceolate leaves, smooth margins, basal and alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Multiple flowers clustered on branched, slender stems (raceme or loose panicle)

balloon flower:  
-Petal Shape: Five inflated, balloon-like buds opening into flat, star-shaped petals with pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Solid vibrant blue to purple, occasionally white or pink variants; uniform color without markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals fused at base, radiating symmetrically in a star formation  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Five prominent dark blue to purple stamens surrounding a central pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Oval to lance-shaped, smooth edges, opposite leaf arrangement along stems  
-Inflorescence Structure: Multiple flowers arising in loose clusters from terminal stems

giant white arum lily:
-Petal Shape: Large, broad, trumpet-shaped spathe with smooth edges
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pure white, uniformly colored spathe
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Single prominent spathe enclosing a central spadix
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Upright, cylindrical yellow or light green spadix densely covered with tiny flowers
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, glossy, arrow-shaped leaves with prominent veins; basal rosette arrangement
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary inflorescence per stalk, emerging from leaf base

fire lily:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly recurved tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Vibrant fiery red to orange with subtle yellow highlights near base; often uniform without spots  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Six petals arranged in two whorls, slightly spreading and reflexed  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent stamens with long, curved filaments and conspicuous anthers; single pistil centrally located  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Long, strap-shaped leaves; basal rosette arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Umbel-like cluster of multiple flowers growing atop a tall, leafless stalk

pincushion flower (genus Scabiosa):  
-Petal Shape: Rounded, slightly notched or scalloped at tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Soft pastel hues including lavender, pink, blue, or white; often uniform, sometimes subtle veining  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Multiple small petals arranged in a dense, circular pattern  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent pincushion-like dome center with numerous protruding stamens tipped with dark anthers  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, lanceolate leaves often lobed or toothed; basal rosette or alternate along stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single, compact flower heads atop slender, long stems; sometimes occasionally branched clusters

fritillary:  
-Petal Shape: Bell-shaped, strongly nodding, petals often recurved backward at tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Typically purple, violet, or brownish with distinct checkerboard or tessellated markings in lighter and darker shades  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Six petals arranged in two whorls of three, forming a symmetrical bell shape  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent yellow or orange stamens clustered around central pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, lanceolate leaves, usually basal and sometimes whorled along the stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Few to several nodding flowers per stem, spaced apart along a slender upright stalk

red ginger:  
-Petal Shape: Bract-like, elongated, waxy, overlapping  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Vivid red to deep crimson, uniform color, glossy surface  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Dense cluster of brightly colored bracts arranged spirally around a central spike; true flowers small and hidden  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Small, tubular, white to yellow flowers emerging between bracts  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, lanceolate, smooth edges; alternate, spirally arranged along stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Upright, cone-shaped, compact spike composed mainly of colorful bracts

grape hyacinth:  
-Petal Shape: Small, urn-shaped, tubular with slightly flared tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Deep blue to violet or sometimes white; uniform color without pattern  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Six fused petals forming a compact cluster of florets in dense racemes  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central stamens usually hidden within the tubular corolla; none prominently visible  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, grass-like, linear leaves; basal arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Dense, cylindrical raceme with tightly packed individual bell-shaped flowers on a single stalk

corn poppy:  
-Petal Shape: Delicate, slightly crinkled, broad oval petals with rounded tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Vivid bright red, sometimes with dark purple or black base blotches near petal base  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 4 to 6 loosely overlapping petals arranged radially  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent dark center with numerous black stamens surrounding a greenish to black pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Deeply lobed or dissected, bluish-green leaves; alternate on stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single or few flowers per slender, hairy stem; flowers nodding before fully opening

prince of wales feathers:  
-Petal Shape: Small, narrow, elongated with rounded tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Distinctive bi-color with greenish base; pink to purple outer edges and markings, sometimes striped or spotted  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 5 petals arranged radially, with two larger upper petals and three smaller lower petals  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central ovary with prominent, protruding stamens bearing contrasting anthers  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Pinnate, fern-like finely divided leaves; alternate arrangement along stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Terminal racemes with multiple flowers clustered on erect stems

stemless gentian:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, trumpet-shaped petals with slightly pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Deep blue to violet, often with lighter veins running longitudinally  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals fused at the base, forming a star-like corolla  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central white stamens partially enclosed by corolla tube; single pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Ovate to lanceolate leaves, opposite or in basal rosettes, sessile  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers close to the ground, appearing nearly stemless or on very short stalks

artichoke:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, tubular florets with pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pale purple to lavender hues; uniform color without markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Dense cluster of numerous small florets tightly packed in a dome shape  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Hidden inside tubular florets, not prominently visible  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, spiny, deeply lobed leaves; gray-green color; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Large, thistle-like flower head resembling a globe with bracted base (involucre)

sweet william:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded with slightly notched tips, somewhat ruffled edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bi-colored or multi-colored, commonly pink, red, white with darker central markings or stripes  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals per flower, symmetrically arranged in a star-like pattern  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central pistil surrounded by stamens, usually not prominent, base often darker  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, lanceolate leaves, opposite arrangement along stems  
-Inflorescence Structure: Dense, rounded clusters (corymb) of small flowers at stem tips

carnation:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded petals with finely serrated or fringed edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Wide color range including pink, red, white, purple; often solid or subtly variegated  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Multiple layers of tightly clustered petals, forming a dense, ruffled bloom  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Generally obscured by dense petals; small, inconspicuous stamens and pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, grass-like, linear leaves; arranged alternately along the stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single or clustered flowers at the stem tips, often solitary but occasionally in small groups

garden phlox:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, slightly notched or rounded tips, tubular base  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Solid colors or bicolor with subtle darker center, commonly pink, white, red, or purple  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals fused at base forming a star-shaped corolla with flat, open face  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central pistil and stamens protrude slightly beyond petals, pale-colored  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Lanceolate, smooth-edged leaves; opposite, sessile attachment  
-Inflorescence Structure: Dense, rounded terminal clusters (panicles) of multiple flowers

love in the mist (Nigella damascena):  
-Petal Shape: Finely divided, narrow, and pointed bract-like petals  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pale blue to soft lavender with occasional darker veins  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals, loosely arranged and separated  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent green bulbous ovary surrounded by multiple thread-like stamens  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Finely dissected, feathery, fern-like leaves; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers held above finely divided foliage, each flower subtended by a whorl of thread-like bracts giving a “misty” appearance

mexican aster:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, linear to lanceolate, slightly curved tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright lavender to purple, sometimes with subtle lighter veins  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Multiple slender ray florets arranged in a single or slightly layered whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent yellow to orange central disc; composed of tightly packed disc florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Lanceolate to ovate, serrated margins, alternate along the stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Loose clusters or solitary flower heads at stem tips

alpine sea holly:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, spiny bracts resembling thistle leaves  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Metallic blue to steel blue bracts; small flowers pale blue to white  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Multiple spiny bracts forming a star-shaped involucre around small clustered florets  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Dense cluster of tiny tubular florets with prominent stamens inside bracts  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Deeply lobed, spiny leaves; basal rosette formation  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single flower head per stem; stem tall and erect with spiny bracts forming a globe-like flower cluster

ruby-lipped cattleya:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded petals and sepals; slightly ruffled edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pale to medium lavender or light purple petals; prominent deep ruby-red to dark magenta lip (labellum) contrasting with petals  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Three petals with one highly modified lip, three sepals similar to petals; symmetrical arrangement  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent column with fused stamens and pistil; lip often larger and ornamented for pollinator landing  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Thick, leathery, oblong to strap-shaped leaves; alternate, arising from pseudobulbs  
-Inflorescence Structure: Terminal raceme with multiple flowers spaced along the stalk

cape flower:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded, slightly overlapping petals with smooth edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright white to pale pink or violet, often with darker purple markings near base  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 5 to 8 petals arranged in a radial symmetry  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent dark purple to black central disc with visible stamens surrounding it  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, lanceolate leaves with a smooth margin; arranged alternately along the stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single flower head per stalk, borne on erect, leafless stems

great masterwort:  
-Petal Shape: Numerous narrow, strap-shaped petals with finely fringed or toothed edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: White or pale pink, uniform coloration without distinct markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 20+ petals arranged in a dense, radiating, star-like pattern  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Dense cluster of small greenish-white florets with prominent stamens and pistils in the center  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Compound leaves with finely divided, feathery leaflets; opposite arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Flat-topped, broad corymb-like clusters of multiple flowers

siam tulip (Curcuma alismatifolia):
-Petal Shape: Broad, ovate to lanceolate petals with smooth edges
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright pink to magenta bracts with lighter pink or white floral petals inside
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Multiple showy bracts overlapping in a spiral or tiered arrangement, with small true flowers nested within
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Small tubular white or pale pink flowers; stamens and pistils typically concealed within bracts
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, elongated, lance-shaped leaves with parallel venation; alternate or basal rosette arrangement
-Inflorescence Structure: Dense, cone-like spike composed of colorful bracts forming a false flower head atop a tall, erect stem

lenten rose:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded to slightly pointed, overlapping sepaloid petals  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Shades of white, pink, purple, greenish, often speckled or veined  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 5-10 sepals arranged in a nodding bowl shape  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent cluster of numerous yellow stamens surrounding a small central pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Broad, leathery, deep green, palmate compound leaves with toothed edges  
-Inflorescence Structure: Nodding, single or grouped flowers emerging from leaf axils on stout stems

barbeton daisy:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly elliptical with smooth edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright golden yellow, uniform color, no markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 13–21 petals arranged in a single, even whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, raised central disc; dark brown to black, densely packed disc florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Oblong to lance-shaped leaves; alternate arrangement, slightly hairy texture  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flower heads on stout, erect stems, often more than one flower per stem possible

daffodil:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated tepals with smooth edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright yellow, white, or pale yellow; solid color without variegation  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Six tepals arranged symmetrically in a single whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent trumpet-shaped corona (cup) in center, often darker or contrasting yellow; stamens partially enclosed inside corona  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Long, narrow, strap-like leaves; basal rosette arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Usually solitary flower per stem, occasionally multiple; stems leafless and erect

sword lily:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, sword-shaped tepals with pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright orange or red with contrasting dark spots or markings near base  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Six tepals arranged in two whorls of three, slightly reflexed  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent stamens with orange pollen; elongated pistil in center  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Long, flat, sword-like leaves; basal rosette or fan-shaped arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Upright spike or raceme with multiple upward-facing flowers spaced along stem

poinsettia:  
-Petal Shape: Small, inconspicuous, tubular or cup-shaped true flowers; large, pointed bracts resembling petals  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bracts typically bright red, also pink, white, or variegated; true flowers yellow-green  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: True flowers grouped centrally in cyathia; usually 4-6 large bracts arranged in a star-like pattern around flowers  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Cyathia containing multiple tiny male stamens and a single female pistil, surrounded by nectar glands  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Broad, ovate to lanceolate leaves with smooth or slightly wavy edges; alternate or spiral arrangement below bracts  
-Inflorescence Structure: Clustered cyathia at stem tips, visually dominated by large colorful bracts resembling petals

bolero deep blue:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded with smooth edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Deep violet-blue with subtle darker veining  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five broad petals arranged in a symmetrical star shape  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent white or pale pistil surrounded by contrasting dark stamens  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, lanceolate leaves with smooth margins; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers at stem tips on erect stalks

wallflower:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, slightly rounded with subtle notches at tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Yellow, orange, or reddish hues; some with faint darker veins  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 4 petals arranged in a cross shape  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent stamens, often yellow; central pistil small and not highly protruding  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, lanceolate to oblong leaves; alternate or basal rosette arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Terminal racemes or clusters, densely packed flowers on short stalks

marigold:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded or slightly ruffled edges; ray florets often overlapping  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Vivid orange, yellow, or reddish-orange; usually solid color without patterns  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Multiple ray florets arranged densely in concentric circles  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central disc often similar in color to petals but more compact, composed of small tubular disc florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Pinnately divided, lanceolate leaflets with serrated edges; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single or clustered flower heads on erect, hairy stems

buttercup:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded, slightly cupped petals  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Glossy bright yellow, uniform color, sometimes with a slight greenish tinge at base  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 5 petals arranged radially, evenly spaced  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Numerous tightly packed yellow stamens surrounding multiple green pistils  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Deeply lobed or toothed leaves, palmate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Usually solitary flowers on slender, erect stems

oxeye daisy:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly rounded tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pure white, uniform color without markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Usually 15-30 ray florets arranged in a single circular whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, convex golden-yellow central disc with tightly packed tiny disc florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Basal leaves spoon-shaped to oblong, toothed margins; smaller leaves alternate along stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary, large flower head at the end of a long, slender, leafless stem

common dandelion:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, strap-shaped ray florets with slightly notched tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright yellow, uniform color without markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Numerous (up to 150) ray florets densely packed in a single head  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): No distinct central disc; reproductive organs fused within ray florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Deeply toothed or lobed basal leaves, rosette arrangement at ground level  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single composite flower head per stem; hollow, leafless, erect stem

petunia:  
-Petal Shape: Funnel-shaped, broad and slightly ruffled edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Wide range including solid colors, bi-color, and speckled or veined patterns; often vivid purples, pinks, reds, whites  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five fused petals forming a single corolla tube with a flared, open face  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Small, inconspicuous central pistil and stamens partially enclosed in corolla tube  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Oval to lanceolate leaves, smooth margins, arranged alternately along stems  
-Inflorescence Structure: Mostly solitary flowers or small clusters positioned at leaf axils or branch tips

wild pansy:  
-Petal Shape: Five asymmetrical petals; two upper petals slightly rounded, two lateral petals slightly obovate with small bases, one lower petal larger and rounded with a slight spur  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Tri-color pattern; typically purple, yellow, and white with dark purple-to-black veining radiating from the floral center  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals arranged in a slightly irregular bilateral symmetry  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Small, yellow floral center with prominent dark veining converging towards it; reproductive organs enclosed within petals  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Heart-shaped or ovate leaves with slightly scalloped edges; alternate and basal rosette arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers on slender stalks arising from the leaf axils or basal rosette

primula:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded or slightly notched tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Typically pastel shades (pink, purple, yellow, white), often with a darker central eye or contrasting throat  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals arranged symmetrically in a flat or slightly cupped corolla  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central pistil surrounded by five stamens often fused into a tube around style  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Rosette of basal leaves, oblong to lanceolate, often wrinkled or crinkled texture  
-Inflorescence Structure: Umbel-like cluster on a single, leafless scape (flower stem) rising from leaf rosette

sunflower:  
-Petal Shape: Long, narrow, slightly pointed ray florets  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright yellow, uniform color without pattern  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Numerous ray florets arranged in a single, circular whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Large, prominent central disc composed of dense, spirally arranged disc florets; color varies from dark brown to deep purple or black  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Broad, ovate to heart-shaped leaves with coarse texture; opposite or alternate arrangement along rough stems  
-Inflorescence Structure: Large, solitary flower head (capitulum) atop tall, sturdy stems

pelargonium:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded to slightly notched; irregular, often with 5 petals, upper petals larger  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Varied; frequently bi-colored or blotched with darker markings or veining on upper petals  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: 5 petals, asymmetrical arrangement, with upper two petals often larger and distinct from lower three  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent pistil and 10 fused stamens in a protruding structure  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Rounded to kidney-shaped or lobed leaves; scalloped edges; opposite arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Umbel-like clusters of flowers borne on long, slender stalks (peduncles)

bishop of llandaff:  
-Petal Shape: Five broad, rounded petals with slightly wavy edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Deep vibrant red, uniform color without markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals arranged symmetrically in a single whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent black stamens with contrasting anthers; central pistil visible  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Lobed, deeply incised leaves; dark green with serrated edges; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Loose clusters of individual flowers at stem tips

gaura:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated with slightly irregular edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Predominantly white or pale pink, sometimes with darker pink veins or spots near the base  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Four petals arranged in an open cross shape, separated and slightly asymmetrical  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent long stamens extending beyond petals, yellow anthers, single central pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Lanceolate to oblong leaves, smooth edges, alternately arranged along stems  
-Inflorescence Structure: Loose, elongated racemes or spikes with multiple flowers spaced apart, each flower nodding on slender pedicels

geranium:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded to slightly notched, broad petals  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Shades of pink, purple, white, often with darker veining or spotting  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 5 petals arranged symmetrically in a single whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent central cluster of 10 stamens, often with dark anthers; pistil central and visible  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Palmately lobed or divided leaves with serrated edges; arranged alternately on stems  
-Inflorescence Structure: Umbel-like clusters of several flowers atop slender stems

orange dahlia:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, slightly pointed, slightly curved or rolled edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright orange, sometimes with subtle yellow or red gradients, uniformly colored without spots  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Numerous tightly packed petals arranged in concentric layers, forming a globe-like or rounded bloom  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Hidden beneath dense petal layers, not prominently visible  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Broad, ovate to lanceolate with serrated margins; opposite or alternate arrangement on stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single, large, terminal flower heads on sturdy, upright stems

pink-yellow dahlia:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, slightly pointed, overlapping petals  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Gradual gradient from soft pink at petal base to pale yellow toward tips  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Dense multiple layers of petals, symmetrically arranged in concentric circles  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Small, less conspicuous central disc, often hidden by inner petal layers  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Ovate to lanceolate leaves with serrated edges; opposite or alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Large, solitary flower heads on stout, upright stems

cautleya spicata:  
-Petal Shape: Tubular to funnel-shaped, slightly curved petals with rounded lobes  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright yellow petals with occasional red or orange blotches/spots near base  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 3 petals forming a prominent labellum with 3 smaller petal-like structures beneath  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent central stamen with a large, curved style; stamen fused forming a column  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Broad, lanceolate leaves with parallel venation; arranged alternately along stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Dense, spike-like racemes with multiple flowers tightly clustered along an erect stem

japanese anemone:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded to slightly ovate, smooth edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Soft pink to white, uniform color without markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: 5 to 7 petals arranged in a single, open whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent cluster of yellow stamens surrounding a greenish, dome-shaped pistil cluster  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Deeply lobed, palmate leaves with toothed margins; basal and alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Loose clusters of flowers on slender, leafless stems

black-eyed susan:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright yellow petals, uniform color, no markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 8-12 ray florets arranged in a single whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, raised dark brown to black central disc with small tubular disc florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Lanceolate to ovate leaves, rough texture, alternate arrangement along the stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flower heads on hairy, erect stems

silverbush:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, linear to slightly spatulate, often with rounded tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Silvery-white to pale gray, sometimes with subtle metallic sheen  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Usually 5 petals arranged symmetrically in a radial pattern  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Small, inconspicuous central reproductive structures; pistil and stamens typically not prominently protruding  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, linear leaves with silvery hairs; opposite or alternate arrangement along stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Compact clusters or solitary flowers often emerging from leaf axils or branch tips

californian poppy:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, cup-shaped, slightly crinkled edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright orange to yellow, sometimes with a gradient from base to tip, no patterning  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Four large petals arranged symmetrically in a single whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Dense cluster of bright yellow stamens surrounding a single pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Finely divided, fern-like, bluish-green leaves; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers on thin, erect stalks that close at night or in cold weather

osteospermum:  
-Petal Shape: Spoon-shaped or slightly spoon-tipped, elongated ray florets  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Wide range including white, purple, pink, blue, often bi-colored with contrasting centers or undersides  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 13–20 ray florets arranged in a single, radial whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, dark blue, purple, or black central disc with tiny tubular disc florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Deeply lobed or toothed leaves, medium green, arranged alternately or in a basal rosette  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary daisy-like flower heads on erect, slender stems

spring crocus:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, lanceolate to ovate, slightly rounded tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pale purple to lilac, sometimes white; uniform color without spots or stripes  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: 6 tepals arranged in a single, symmetrical whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Bright orange to yellow stamens, central pistil often yellow; stamens clustered  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Grass-like, linear leaves with a central white stripe; basal arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Usually solitary flower per stem, arising directly from corm, low to ground level

bearded iris:  
-Petal Shape: Three upright "standards" and three downward "falls" with ruffled edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Varied colors often with contrasting darker veining or patterns on falls  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Six petals in two distinct whorls (three up, three down)  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent yellow or orange fuzzy "beard" on each fall petal; visible stamens beneath standards  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Sword-shaped, long, narrow leaves; fan-like basal arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Multiple flowers arranged on a tall, erect stem, spaced apart

windflower:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded petals with slightly wavy edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Mostly white, pale pink, or blue; often solid color without distinct markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 5 to 8 petals arranged in a single, open whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent cluster of bright yellow stamens; greenish or dark central pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Deeply lobed or dissected leaves; basal rosette or alternate stem leaves  
-Inflorescence Structure: Usually solitary flowers on slender, erect stems

tree poppy:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded with slightly wrinkled or crinkled texture  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright yellow to golden, uniform without spots or markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 4 large petals, arranged in a simple, open cup shape  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Numerous yellow stamens densely clustered around a green, prominent, multi-lobed pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Deeply lobed, pinnate leaves with toothed margins; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers at stem tips on stout, erect stems

gazania:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright colors including yellow, orange, red, often with dark central stripes or spots near base  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: 12 to 20 ray florets arranged in a single, symmetrical whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, dense yellow or orange central disc with visible disc florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow, lanceolate, sometimes deeply lobed or toothed; basal rosette or alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flower heads on erect, leafless stalks

azalea:  
-Petal Shape: Funnel-shaped, slightly ruffled or smooth edges, often with a slight flare at the tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Wide range including pink, white, red, purple, often with blotches or speckles near the throat  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 5 petals, arranged symmetrically in a single whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, long stamens (usually 5-10) extending beyond petals, slender pistil visible  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Small to medium, elliptical or ovate leaves, often evergreen, arranged alternately or clustered near flowers  
-Inflorescence Structure: Clustered terminal or axillary trusses of multiple flowers (3-10 per cluster)

water lily:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded, slightly pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: White, pink, yellow, or purple hues; solid color, sometimes with subtle gradients  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Numerous petals arranged in concentric whorls, overlapping tightly  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent dense cluster of bright yellow stamens surrounding a central pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, round, flat floating leaves with smooth or slightly wavy edges; radial arrangement on water surface  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers emerging directly from submerged stems, floating on or just above water surface

rose:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded with slightly wavy or scalloped edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Wide color range including red, pink, white, yellow; typically solid colors, sometimes gradient or striped  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Multiple layers (often 5 to 60+) of tightly overlapping petals forming a dense, cup-shaped bloom  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Often hidden beneath dense petals, central pistil surrounded by numerous yellow stamens when visible  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Pinnate leaves with 3-9 oval, serrated leaflets; alternate arrangement on stems  
-Inflorescence Structure: Usually solitary flowers or small clusters, borne on prickly stems

thorn apple:  
-Petal Shape: Trumpet-shaped, funnel-like with flared lobes  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pale purple to white with dark purple or violet veining/spots  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five fused petals forming a single corolla tube, lobes spreading radially  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent central pistil with five long, protruding stamens attached near corolla throat  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, ovate to lanceolate with smooth or slightly wavy margins; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers emerging from leaf axils on stout peduncles

morning glory:  
-Petal Shape: Funnel-shaped, flaring widely at the mouth  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Solid or gradient shades of blue, purple, pink, white, or magenta; often with a white or pale throat  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five fused petals forming a single corolla tube  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Five prominent stamens fused around the pistil, visible in the throat  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Heart-shaped (cordate) leaves; alternate arrangement along the stem  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary or paired flowers arising from leaf axils on long peduncles

passion flower:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly curved petals with slender filaments forming corona  
-Petal Color and Pattern: White to purple petals; central corona filaments often banded in contrasting colors (purple, white, blue, or green)  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals and five sepals arranged in a radial symmetry beneath corona filaments  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent central structure with five stamens extending horizontally and three styles with bulbous stigmas above  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Palmate lobed leaves, usually 3-5 lobes, alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary or paired flowers emerging from leaf axils on slender peduncles

lotus:
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded with smooth edges, slightly overlapping  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Typically pale pink to white, occasionally with subtle gradient from base to tip  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Numerous (12-20+), arranged in multiple concentric whorls  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, large yellow receptacle shaped like a flattened cone or dish, surrounded by numerous slender yellow stamens  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, circular leaves with wavy edges, often floating or held above water on long petioles  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers borne on stout, erect stalks rising above the water surface

toad lily:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly recurved or twisted petals  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pale background (white, cream, or light purple) with dense, contrasting dark purple or maroon spots  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically six tepals arranged in two whorls of three  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent stamens with yellow anthers, slightly protruding pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Lanceolate to ovate leaves, opposite or alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single or few flowers emerging from leaf axils, drooping or horizontally oriented

anthurium:  
-Petal Shape: Single, large, heart-shaped or ovate spathe  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright red, pink, white, or green; solid color, smooth texture  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: One prominent spathe surrounding the floral spike  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent cylindrical spadix with densely packed tiny flowers  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, glossy, heart-shaped or lanceolate leaves; basal rosette or alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single spadix emerging centrally from the spathe, upright and erect

frangipani:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded, slightly overlapping, broad petals with smooth edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: White or cream base with a vibrant yellow center; sometimes pink or red edges  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals arranged symmetrically in a spiral or pinwheel pattern  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent yellow to orange throat; stamens not easily visible externally  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, elongated elliptical leaves with smooth margin; opposite or whorled arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Clustered terminal umbels with multiple flowers forming tight bunches

clematis:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, ovate to lanceolate tepals (sepals resembling petals), slightly pointed tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Wide color range including purple, blue, white, pink; solid or slightly variegated, often with prominent veins  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 4 to 8 tepals per flower, arranged in a radial, star-like pattern  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent cluster of numerous elongated stamens with contrasting colors, often yellow anthers  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Compound leaves with 3-5 leaflets, ovate to lanceolate, opposite or alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Mostly solitary flowers or small clusters at stem tips

hibiscus:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, overlapping, slightly ruffled or wavy edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Solid colors often bright red, pink, white, yellow, or orange; sometimes with contrasting central eye or gradient shading  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: 5 large, symmetric petals arranged in a radial pattern  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent protruding column of fused stamens and style with yellow pollen sacs; pistil tip usually 5-lobed  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Broad ovate to lanceolate leaves with serrated margins; alternate leaf arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Usually solitary large flowers arising from leaf axils on long stalks

columbine:  
-Petal Shape: Distinctive elongated spurs extending backward; petals often rounded to slightly flared at tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Varied colors including blue, purple, red, yellow, and white; often bicolored with contrasting spurs and petal bodies  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals with five sepals, arranged radially with spurred petals alternating with sepals  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent cluster of long, protruding yellow stamens centrally located  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Lobed or compound leaves with rounded to slightly toothed edges; basal rosette and alternate stem leaves  
-Inflorescence Structure: Loose clusters of nodding flowers on slender, erect stalks

desert-rose:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded with slightly wavy margins  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Glossy pink to deep rose, often with darker pink or red edges and white to light pink central streaks  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals arranged symmetrically in a single whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central pistil surrounded by five stamens fused at base, prominently visible  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Thick, succulent, oblong to oval leaves; opposite arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Clustered terminal blooms, often 3-5 flowers per inflorescence

tree mallow:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded with slightly notched tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pale pink to lilac, sometimes with darker pink veins radiating from the center  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals arranged symmetrically in a single whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent central column of fused stamens, yellowish or cream-colored  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Palmate, 5-7 lobed leaves with serrated edges, alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Clusters of flowers (raceme or panicle) typically found at branch tips

magnolia:
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded, thick and waxy texture  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Usually white, pink, purple, or cream; solid coloration without markings  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: 6 to 12 large petals arranged in multiple overlapping whorls  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent cone-shaped reproductive structure with numerous tightly packed stamens and pistils  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, ovate to elliptical leaves with smooth edges; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary, large flowers borne at branch tips or axils

cyclamen:  
-Petal Shape: Upswept, reflexed petals with a twisted or curled appearance  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Solid pink, white, red, or purple; occasionally bi-colored or with darker markings near base  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 5 petals per flower, symmetrically arranged around the center  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Central mass of short stamens clustered around a single pistil; often inconspicuous  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Rounded to heart-shaped leaves with scalloped or slightly serrated edges; variegated or plain green; basal rosette arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Single flowers or small clusters held on slender, leafless stalks emerging from the leaf rosette

watercress:
-Petal Shape: Small, rounded, slightly notched at tips
-Petal Color and Pattern: White, uniform color, no pattern
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Four petals arranged in a cross shape (cruciform)
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Yellow stamens, central pistil visible
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Pinnately compound leaves with rounded or slightly lobed leaflets; alternate arrangement
-Inflorescence Structure: Dense clusters (racemes) of small flowers at stem tips

canna lily:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, slightly ruffled or wavy edges, rounded tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Vivid colors including red, orange, yellow, often with speckled or streaked patterns  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: 3 large asymmetrical petals with 3 smaller petal-like staminodes; irregular overlapping arrangement  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, protruding stamens fused with petal-like structures, often curved  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Large, broad, elongated lanceolate leaves with smooth margins, spiral or alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Upright, dense clusters (panicles) on tall stalks with flowers arranged spirally or alternately along the stem

hippeastrum:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, trumpet-shaped, slightly ruffled edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Typically solid colors or striped; shades range from red, pink, white to orange with contrasting central veins or banding  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Six petals arranged symmetrically in two whorls of three  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent stamens with large anthers extending beyond petals; central pistil with a three-lobed stigma  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Strap-shaped, glossy green leaves; basal, arising from bulb  
-Inflorescence Structure: Umbel-like cluster of large flowers on a tall, leafless scape

bee balm:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, tubular petals with ruffled or jagged edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright red, pink, purple, or white; often solid color without pattern  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Numerous petals clustered densely in a spherical or spiky head  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, protruding stamens and pistils extending beyond petals  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Opposite, ovate to lanceolate leaves with serrated margins  
-Inflorescence Structure: Dense, rounded terminal clusters (capitula) atop square stems

ball moss:  
-Petal Shape: Tiny, tubular, narrow petals  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pale green to yellowish, often inconspicuous  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 3 to 5 petals per flower, fused at base  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Small, central reproductive structures mostly hidden inside petals  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Scale-like, overlapping leaves closely attached to stems  
-Inflorescence Structure: Small clusters attached to host plant; flowers appear axillary or terminal on ball-like tufts

foxglove:  
-Petal Shape: Tubular, bell-shaped, flared opening  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Usually purple, pink, white, or yellow; spotted or speckled throat contrasting with base color  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five fused petals forming a bilateral, elongated corolla; arranged in a downward-facing cluster  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Four prominent, enclosed stamens inside the corolla tube; single pistil centrally located  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Broad, ovate to lanceolate leaves with serrated edges; basal rosette and alternate stem leaves  
-Inflorescence Structure: Tall, erect spike with multiple flowers arranged vertically, nodding downward

bougainvillea:  
-Petal Shape: Tiny, tubular, and inconspicuous true flowers  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Surrounding large, papery bracts in vibrant magenta, pink, red, orange, white, or purple; solid color, smooth texture  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: True flowers have 5 small petals; bracts typically grouped in clusters of three surrounding the flower  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent white or yellow stamens protruding from tubular flowers; pistil small and less conspicuous  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Ovate to elliptical leaves with smooth margins; opposite or alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Dense clusters of 3 bracts subtending a small, central true flower; often in terminal or axillary clusters

camellia:  
-Petal Shape: Rounded or slightly ruffled, smooth edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Solid colors, commonly white, pink, red, or variegated with subtle gradients  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Multiple overlapping petals arranged in a spiral or concentric layers, often dense and full  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent cluster of yellow stamens, sometimes partially hidden by petals; pistil central but less conspicuous  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Glossy, dark green, elliptical or ovate leaves with serrated margins; alternate arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Usually solitary flowers, sometimes clusters, emerging from leaf axils

mallow:
-Petal Shape: Broad, rounded with slightly wavy edges
-Petal Color and Pattern: Pale pink to purple with darker purple or deep pink veins radiating from the base
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Five petals arranged radially and overlapping slightly
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent central column of fused stamens surrounding pistil, yellowish to brownish anthers
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Palmately lobed, broad with toothed margins; alternate arrangement
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers or small clusters on slender stalks arising from leaf axils

mexican petunia:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly rounded tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Solid vibrant purple, lilac, or white; uniform coloration without spots or stripes  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 5 petals arranged in a single, flat radial symmetry  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent white or pale pistil with yellow stamens; central reproductive structures slightly raised  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Lanceolate to ovate leaves; opposite arrangement on stems  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flowers or small clusters at leaf axils on erect, slender stems

bromelia:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, tubular to slightly flared petals  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright colors, commonly red, orange, yellow; sometimes with green or purple tinges  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Typically 3 petals forming a symmetrical flower  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent central pistil with 3 stamens often fused at the base  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Long, rigid, strap-like leaves arranged in a rosette pattern  
-Inflorescence Structure: Central, compact flower spike emerging from leaf rosette, often surrounded by colorful bracts

blanket flower:  
-Petal Shape: Narrow, elongated, slightly pointed, often with irregular or notched tips  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright red, orange, or yellow base with distinct yellow tips or bands; sometimes bi-colored rays  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Multiple ray florets arranged in a single, circular whorl  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, raised dome-shaped central disc; reddish-brown to dark maroon with tightly packed disc florets  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Narrow to lanceolate leaves, sometimes toothed or lobed; alternate or basal clustering  
-Inflorescence Structure: Solitary flower heads atop slender, erect stems

trumpet creeper:
-Petal Shape: Large, trumpet-shaped, flared tubular corolla with five rounded lobes  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Bright orange to reddish-orange, often with subtle darker veining inside the tube  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Single flower with five fused petals forming a trumpet; lobes arranged radially  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Four long, exserted stamens protruding beyond the corolla; single pistil centrally located  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Pinnately compound leaves with 7–11 oval to lanceolate leaflets, serrated edges, opposite arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Clusters of tubular flowers arranged in terminal or axillary panicles or racemes

blackberry lily:  
-Petal Shape: Broad, lanceolate with slightly wavy edges  
-Petal Color and Pattern: Yellow base with prominent reddish-brown spots covering entire petal surface  
-Petal Number and Arrangement: Six petals arranged in two whorls (outer and inner) of three each  
-Floral Center (stamens, pistil, disc): Prominent, six yellow stamens with curved filaments and an elongated central pistil  
-Leaf Shape and Arrangement: Long, narrow, lanceolate leaves with parallel venation; alternate or basal arrangement  
-Inflorescence Structure: Terminal raceme with multiple flowers spaced along a single stalk
